>
  <h1>Gratuity and End-of-Service Benefits in the Gulf: 2026 Guide</h1>

  <p>End-of-service gratuity is one of the most valuable financial benefits of working in the Gulf. Unlike Western pension systems that accumulate over decades, Gulf gratuity provides a lump-sum payment when you leave your job, creating a significant cash windfall at career transitions. This guide explains how gratuity works in the UAE, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia, with formulas, examples, and key differences.</p>

  <h2>Gratuity Formulas by Country</h2>
  <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto mb-8">
    <table class="w-full text-sm">
      <thead><tr class="bg-teal-600 text-white"><th class="px-4 py-3 text-left rounded-tl-lg">Factor</th><th class="px-4 py-3 text-center">UAE</th><th class="px-4 py-3 text-center">Qatar</th><th class="px-4 py-3 text-center rounded-tr-lg">Saudi Arabia</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
        <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">First 5 years</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">21 days/year</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">21 days/year</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">15 days/year</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">After 5 years</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">30 days/year</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">21 days/year</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">30 days/year</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Salary basis</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">Basic only</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">Basic only</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">Basic + housing</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Payment deadline</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">14 days</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">7 days</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">No fixed deadline</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium">Cap</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">2 years' salary</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">No cap</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-center">No cap</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>UAE Gratuity Rules</h2>
  <p>Under UAE Federal Decree-Law No. 33 of 2021, employees are entitled to gratuity after completing one year of continuous service. The formula is 21 days of basic salary per year for the first 5 years, and 30 days per year thereafter. The total is capped at 2 years' total salary. Daily salary is calculated as monthly basic salary divided by 30. For example, an employee with AED 15,000 basic salary and 7 years of service receives: (15,000/30 x 21 x 5) + (15,000/30 x 30 x 2) = AED 52,500 + AED 30,000 = AED 82,500. Resignation penalties apply for limited contracts terminated early and for unlimited contracts with less than 5 years of service. Our <a href="/uae/gratuity-calculator/">UAE Gratuity Calculator</a> handles all scenarios automatically.</p>

  <h2>Saudi Arabia Gratuity Rules</h2>
  <p>Saudi labor law calculates gratuity on the total of basic salary plus housing allowance, which is a significant advantage over the UAE's basic-only formula. The rate is half a month's salary per year for the first 5 years, and a full month per year thereafter. There is no cap. For example, an employee earning SAR 12,000 basic + SAR 5,000 housing (SAR 17,000 total) with 8 years of service receives: (17,000/2 x 5) + (17,000 x 3) = SAR 42,500 + SAR 51,000 = SAR 93,500. Resignation penalties are graduated: less than 2 years gives one-third, 2-5 years gives two-thirds, 5-10 years gives full if employer terminates or two-thirds if employee resigns, 10+ years gives full in all cases. Use our <a href="/saudi-arabia/gratuity-calculator/">Saudi Gratuity Calculator</a> for exact figures.</p>

  <h2>Qatar Gratuity Rules</h2>
  <p>Qatar's formula is the simplest: a minimum of 3 weeks (21 days) of basic salary per year, with no tier change regardless of service length. The daily rate is basic salary divided by 30, multiplied by 21 days per year. For example, an employee with QAR 10,000 basic salary and 6 years of service receives: (10,000/30) x 21 x 6 = QAR 42,000. Qatar has the strictest payment deadline: 7 days after employment ends. Resignation penalties are harsh for short service: zero for under 2 years, one-third for 2-5 years, two-thirds for 5-10 years, and full after 10 years. The Workers' Support and Insurance Fund protects workers if employers fail to pay. Calculate your Qatar entitlement with our <a href="/qatar/gratuity-calculator/">Qatar Gratuity Calculator</a>.</p>

  <h2>Which Country Offers the Best Gratuity?</h2>
  <p>For most employees serving 5-10 years, Saudi Arabia produces the largest gratuity amounts because the calculation includes housing allowance on top of basic salary. The UAE's 30-day rate after 5 years provides a meaningful boost for long-serving employees, but the 2-year cap limits total payouts for very high earners. Qatar's uniform 21-day rate is the simplest but least generous for long tenures. When planning your Gulf career, factor gratuity into your total compensation analysis. A 5-year stint in Saudi Arabia with a SAR 20,000 basic + housing package yields approximately SAR 50,000 in gratuity, which represents a meaningful addition to your savings.</p>

  <h2>Common Mistakes and Disputes</h2>
  <p>Gratuity disputes are among the most common labor complaints filed in all three Gulf countries. The most frequent issue is disagreement over the salary basis used for calculation. Employers sometimes attempt to calculate gratuity on basic salary alone when the contract does not clearly separate basic from total pay, or when housing allowance should be included (as in Saudi Arabia). Employees should request a written salary breakdown at the time of hiring, ensuring that basic salary and allowances are clearly defined in the employment contract. Another common mistake is miscounting service duration. Periods of unpaid leave may or may not count toward total service depending on the country and the reason for the leave. Maternity leave and sick leave are generally counted as continuous service in all three countries. Employees who have worked for partial years should verify that their pro-rated portion is correctly calculated, as this is often rounded down by employers.</p>

  <h2>Strategies to Maximize Your Gratuity</h2>
  <p>Several practical strategies can help you maximize your gratuity payout. First, negotiate a higher basic salary relative to allowances during your initial offer, since gratuity is calculated on basic salary (or basic plus housing in Saudi Arabia) rather than total package value. A compensation package of AED 20,000 with AED 14,000 basic produces significantly more gratuity than the same total package with AED 10,000 basic. Second, consider the impact of service duration thresholds. In Saudi Arabia, completing 10 years of service eliminates all resignation penalties, entitling you to the full gratuity regardless of who initiated the separation. In the UAE, the 5-year mark triggers the higher 30-day rate. Timing your departure to cross these thresholds can add thousands to your final payout. Third, maintain detailed records of your employment dates, salary changes, and any periods of leave, as these all affect the final calculation. Finally, if you are contemplating a move between Gulf countries, compare the gratuity systems as part of your total compensation analysis, since the differences between countries can amount to tens of thousands over a full career.</p>

  <h2>Filing a Gratuity Complaint</h2>
  <p>If your employer fails to pay your gratuity or offers an amount below what the law requires, you have recourse through the labor dispute systems in each country. In the UAE, the first step is filing a complaint through the MoHRE smart app or website. MoHRE will attempt mediation between you and your employer. If mediation fails within 14 days, the case is referred to the labor court, where a judge will review the employment contract, salary records, and service duration to determine the correct gratuity amount. Legal proceedings in the UAE are generally resolved within two to four months. In Saudi Arabia, disputes are handled through the Labor Courts, with initial complaints filed through the MHRSD online portal. The courts have become increasingly efficient, with most straightforward gratuity cases resolved within one to three months. Qatar's dispute mechanism begins with MADLSA, which mediates between the parties. If mediation fails, the case moves to the Labor Dispute Resolution Committee. Qatar's Workers' Support and Insurance Fund can also intervene to pay owed gratuity directly to employees when employers are unable to meet their obligations, providing an important safety net that does not exist in the other two countries.</p>

  <h2>Gratuity and the UAE's Voluntary Savings Scheme</h2>
  <p>The UAE has introduced a voluntary alternative savings scheme that allows employers to invest end-of-service gratuity contributions into regulated investment funds rather than holding them as a balance sheet liability. Under this scheme, employers make monthly contributions equivalent to the gratuity accrual into approved investment vehicles managed by licensed fund managers in the Dubai International Financial Centre (DIFC). Employees benefit from potential investment returns that can exceed the statutory gratuity amount, and the funds are ring-fenced from the employer's business operations, reducing the risk of non-payment if the company faces financial difficulties. Participation in the scheme is voluntary for both employers and employees. If your employer offers this option, compare the projected investment returns against the guaranteed statutory gratuity to determine which arrangement better serves your financial goals. The scheme reflects a broader trend in the Gulf toward modernizing retirement benefits for expatriates, and similar proposals are under discussion in Saudi Arabia and Qatar.</p>

  <h2>How Unpaid Leave and Absences Affect Gratuity</h2>
  <p>The treatment of absences and unpaid leave varies across the three Gulf countries and can meaningfully affect your final gratuity calculation. In the UAE, periods of unpaid leave are generally excluded from the calculation of total service duration, meaning that extended unpaid absences will reduce your gratuity entitlement. Sick leave and maternity leave, on the other hand, are counted as continuous service under UAE labor law. In Saudi Arabia, the position is similar: authorized leave periods such as annual leave, sick leave, and maternity leave count toward continuous service, while unauthorized absences of more than 20 days in a single year, or 10 consecutive days, may constitute grounds for dismissal and can affect gratuity eligibility. Qatar follows a comparable approach, with authorized leave counting as service and unauthorized absences potentially impacting entitlement. If you anticipate needing extended leave during your employment, clarify with your employer's HR department whether the absence will be classified as paid leave, unpaid leave, or leave without pay, and understand the implications for both your service continuity and gratuity calculation. Maintaining written records of all approved leave requests and the corresponding HR approvals provides important documentation if a dispute arises at the end of your employment.</p>

  <h2>Gratuity When Transferring Between Group Companies</h2>
  <p>A frequently overlooked scenario involves employees who transfer between subsidiaries or related entities within the same corporate group. In the UAE, if you move from one legal entity to another, even within the same group, your gratuity must be settled by the original employer unless a written agreement specifies that service is continuous across entities and gratuity liability transfers to the new employer. Without such an agreement, the transfer effectively resets your service clock for gratuity purposes, which can result in a significant loss of accumulated entitlement, particularly if you had crossed the five-year threshold. In Saudi Arabia, a similar principle applies: continuous service for gratuity purposes is calculated per employer unless a formal transfer arrangement preserves accumulated service. Before accepting an internal transfer between group companies, request written confirmation that your total service period will be preserved for gratuity calculation purposes. This is especially important for senior employees with long tenures, where the difference between a fresh start and continuous service can amount to tens of thousands in the local currency. Employees in Qatar should seek the same written assurance, as the law does not automatically recognize inter-company transfers within a group as continuous service for gratuity calculation.</p>

